{"key":"processedPost-15293112","value":{"id":15293112,"first":15292641,"last":15313537,"when":1319859681,"utime":"10/29/11 06:41 AM","content":"If it has a toggle valve, it's probably a sterilizer. The difference is that if the rubber blowout plug is sealing properly, a sterilizer will pull a vacuum on cool down, while a pressure cooker will not.<br /><br />Run it with the toggle valve open for a few minutes each time.&nbsp; This vents all the air out of the unit and replaces it with steam.&nbsp; Then, close the toggle and build pressure.&nbsp; You'll have to adjust the stove setting to obtain the desired pressure.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pressure canner vs. sterilizer?"}}